[[File:Lung cancer in L. Bronchus - bronchoscopic view.png|thumb|A view of cancerous growths in the airway of the left lung, as seen through a bronchoscope.]]'''Bronchoscopy''' is a medical procedure which is used to look at the inside of a person's airway's. It can be used to see the inside of the [[trachea]], and the [[bronchi]] and [[bronchiole]]s within the lungs. There are three types of bronchoscopy: rigid, flexible fiberoptic bronchoscopy and CT virtual bronchoscopy (CTVB).

==Rigid bronchoscopy==
Rigid bronchoscopy is a straight rigid tube used to see into the trachea and proximal bronchi. It is usually done in an operating room under general [[anesthesia]]. It is usually used when there is a blockage in either the trachea or the primary bronchi. The diameter of the tube is large enough to insert instruments to remove obstructions.<ref>David P. Naidich: Imaging Of The Airways: Functional And Radiologic Correlations. Lippincott Williams & Wilkins; 1 edition (2005) p.30 ISBN 0781757681</ref>

==Flexible fiberoptic bronchoscopy==
During the procedure, a thin, flexible [[Fiber optic|fiberoptic]] tube called a bronchoscope. is passed through the nose or mouth nose into the airways. The bronchoscope has a light and a camera which lets the doctor see into the airway.<ref>Pallav Shah: Atlas of Flexible Bronchoscopy. CRC Press; 1 edition (2011) pp. I-II ISBN 034096832X</ref>  
  
